<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="59">Taxon classification Animalia Diptera Bombyliidae</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="59" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="59">
Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Scopoli" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthrax Scopoli</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="59" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="59">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="59">
This is a diverse genus with 248 species worldwide. Two old but complete revisions of the genus, including distribution maps and keys, were made by 
<bibRefCitation author="Marston, N" journalOrPublisher="Technical Bulletin of the Kansas State University Agricultural Experiment Station" pageId="30" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 79" title="A revision of the Nearctic species of the albofasciatus group of the genus Anthrax Scopoli (Diptera: Bombyliidae)." volume="127" year="1963">Marston (1963</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Marston, N" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C." pageId="30" pageNumber="79" title="Revision of New World species of Anthrax (Diptera: Bombyliidae), other than the Anthrax albofasciatus group." url="10.5479/si.00810282.43" year="1970">1970</bibRefCitation>
). Thanks to these 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthrax</taxonomicName>
species can be easily identified. Some 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthrax</taxonomicName>
species are widely distributed occupying two biogeographic regions. From the seven 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthrax</taxonomicName>
species collected in this study in Coahuila, just 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax cybele" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cybele">Anthrax cybele</taxonomicName>
(Coquillett, 1894) has a restricted distribution. The other six species are widespread across the Nearctic region. Two species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Anthrax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthrax" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anthrax</taxonomicName>
are reported for the first time for Mexico.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
